6:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-12","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Rate Mechanics"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"OKX uses traditional 8-hour funding intervals with TWAP-based premium calculation, while Vertex implements hourly funding on Arbitrum with cross-margin efficiency. OKX's longer intervals create larger funding jumps but more predictable timing for arbitrageurs. Vertex's hourly system provides smoother rate adjustments and faster mean reversion, though requiring more active position management. Both use similar premium/index price differentials but Vertex's on-chain settlement adds gas considerations."}]]}]
7:["$","$Lb",null,{"items":[{"question":"Which exchange has better funding rate arbitrage opportunities?","answer":"Vertex's hourly funding intervals create more frequent arbitrage windows, while OKX's 8-hour cycles offer larger but less frequent opportunities. Vertex suits active traders; OKX works better for set-and-forget strategies."},{"question":"How do trading fees impact funding rate profits?","answer":"Vertex's 0.03% taker fee vs OKX's 0.05% creates significant savings for frequent rebalancing. On a $10k position rebalanced daily, Vertex saves $20 per cycle, meaningfully impacting arbitrage returns."},{"question":"What are the main risks when arbitraging between these platforms?","answer":"Cross-chain bridging delays between OKX and Vertex's Arbitrum settlement can create timing mismatches. Vertex's sequencer dependency and OKX's potential KYC restrictions add operational risks to consider."},{"question":"Which platform handles large funding rate positions better?","answer":"OKX's deeper liquidity and portfolio margin handle large positions more efficiently. Vertex's cross-margin helps with capital efficiency but liquidity constraints may impact execution on significant size."}]}]
